@selvaganesang the CQD change does not get widely support in the community. HIVE_MAX_STRING_LENGTH is already widely used, we should keep it and add a new CQD for now. And mark HIVE_MAX_STRING_LENGTH as deprecated. Until we make sure it is no longer used, we can remove it.
So let me add a new CQD HIVE_MAX_STRING_LENGTH_IN_BYTES as Dave suggested, and keep the current CQD unchanged.

Looks good to me, but I just have a question: Usually, a process calls msg_init_attach() to initialize its environment in Trafodion. The sqInit() method seems to do only part of that. Is that ok?
file_init_attach is called from my_mpi_setup and my_mpi_setup is called in sqInit. We need to do file_init_attach to get the node id of the process. The node id is part of the log file name.

Looks good to me. Thanks for this update.

That will eventually be through the query invalidation feature. Right now I don't think ALTER of UDF or LIBRARY will cause query invalidation to kick in. We may need to add invalidation key for LIBRARY object and include library in the list of objects used by a query. I updated the checkin comment to say compiler cache instead of caches.

So, the behavior with this change is that the altered library is immediately visible in the session where ALTER LIBRARY is done, and in any new sessions that start afterward. However, for existing sessions it depends on whether something has been referenced from that library yet. Is this correct?
Is the user expected to move the jar and ddl files prior to issuing this command.
Please add the information about how this change was tested?

Hi Dave. Yes. We do not cache a library definition per se in the NARoutine cache. We do cache naroutines for Routine objects which will be using the library. 

Hi Selva, The ALTER command will check for existence of the file referred to in the FILE clause. If not found it will raise an error.

In that case, will the alter command remove the files from the old location. If there is no query invalidation or if it isn't removed from old location, then the user might see unexpected behavior from UDF/UDR calls till DCS is restarted.  Won't it be confusing then?
